Learning objectives

  • Understand the functions of thedigestive system
  • Describe the anatomy of themouth, stomach, small intestine and large intestine
  • Describe mechanisms and functions of motilities of the digestive system
  • Explain the processes involved in digestion and absorption of nutrients including the role played by thedifferent parts of the digestive system and associated glands
  • Suggested reading
    • Saladin, Anatomy & Physiology: The Unity of Form and Function 9e
      • 25.1-23.7

Function of the digestive system

  • The functions of the digestive system include
    • Processing food
    • Nutrient extraction and absorption
    • Eliminates the residue
  • These functions are performed over 5 stages:
    • Ingestion
    • Digestion
      • Mechanical
      • Chemical
    • Absorption
    • Compaction
    • Defecation

Anatomy of the digestive system

Figure 25.1

Figure 25.2

The mouth

  • The functions of the mouth include
    • Ingestion or intake of food
    • Mechanical digestion (mastication or chewing)
    • Chemical digestion
    • Swallowing
    • Taste and smell of food
    • Others: speech, respiration
  • Also consider cheeks, lips, tongue, the palate and teeth
  • Mastication requires little thought as food stimulates oral receptors to evoke an automatic reflex
  • Saliva
    • Moistens and cleans the mouth, dissolves molecules so they can stimulate taste buds
    • Digests a little starch and fat, also binds and lubricates food to make it easier for swallowing
    • Produced by both intrinsic (a number of small glads in tongue, lips, palate and cheeks) and extrinsic(parotid, submandibular and sublingual glands)
    • Salivatorynuclei respond to a wide range of direct stimuli and parasympathetic stimulation

Swallowing

  • Occurs in three phases
    • The oral phase (voluntary)
      • Tongue collects food, press it against the palate and pushes posteriorly
      • When the bolus reaches critical size in the oropharynx, epiglottis tipsposteriorly and bolus slides into the laryngopharynx
    • Pharyngeal phase (involuntary)
      • Upperesophaguswidens and pharyngeal constrictors contract in order(superior, middle, inferior) to drive the bolus into theesophagus
      • The soft palate and root of the tongue prevent food from entering the nasalcavity or mouth
      • The larynx is pulled up to the epiglottis and vocal cords adduct to close theairway
    • Esophagealphase (involuntary)
      • Peristalsis (a wave of constriction in the smooth muscle) pushes the bolusdown theesophagus
      • When the bolus reaches the lower end, theesophagealsphincter relaxes tolet the bolus pass into the stomach

Figure 23.1

The stomach

  • The stomach is a J-shaped muscular sac that functions include:
    • Food storage
    • Mechanically breaks up food particles and liquefies food
    • Begins chemical digestion of proteins and fats
    • Produceschyme

Figure 25.12

The stomach: mucosa

  • The stomach mucosa consists of simple columnarglandular epithelium
  • The mucosa contains depressions called gastric pits
  • Tubular glands (cardial, pyloric or gastric) open into thebottom of each pit and consist of:
    • Mucous cells: contain mucin, becomes mucous whensecreted
    • Regenerative (stem) cells: at the base, provide acontinuous supply of cells
    • Parietal cells: in the upper half, secrete hydrochloricacid, ghrelin and intrinsic factor
    • Chief cells: in lower half (but most numerous),secrete enzymes gastric lipase and pepsinogen
    • Enteroendocrine cells: in the lower end, secretehormones and paracrine messengers

Figure 25.13

The stomach: motility

  • The stomach reacts to swallowing with a receptive-relaxation response
    • Mechanoreceptors in pharynx; medulla oblongata;vagusnerves; stomach
  • The presence of food in the stomach evokes peristaltic contractions
    • Generated by enteric pacemaker cells
    • Peak at around 30 minutes
  • Contraction waves
    • Leading wave closes pyloric valve
    • Trailing wave mixeschymeand small amount enters the duodenum
  • Vomiting involves multiple muscle actions coordinated by the emetic centre of the medulla oblongata
    • Thoracic expansion, abdominal contractions, opening of theesophagealsphincter and reverseperistalsis

The stomach: regulation

Figure 25.17

The liver, gallbladder and pancreas

  • The liver is gland that is involved in digestion by:
    • Secreting bile that travels into the small intestine via hepatic duct and bile duct
    • Receives blood from the stomach, intestines, pancreas and spleen via hepatic portal vein
      • All nutrients except for lipids
  • The gallbladder is sac on the underside of liver that stores and concentrates (by absorbing water andsolutes) bile
    • It stores bile produced by the liver (receives overflow from the bile duct between meals)
  • The pancreas is an endocrine (insulin and glucagon) and exocrine (pancreatic juice) gland
    • Pancreatic juice is a mixture of water, enzymes, zymogens, sodium bicarbonate and electrolytes
  • Pancreatic juice and bile
    • Regulated byvagusand local nerves, Cholecystokinin (CCK) produced by duodenum and jejunum, and,secretin
    • Bile is important for the digestion of fats
    • Enzymes are import for the digestion of proteins, fats, and DNA
    • Sodium bicarbonate is import for neutralisingHCl(protection) and raising pH for enzymes

The small intestine

  • Chemical digestion and nutrient absorption occurs inthe small intestine
  • Requires a large surface area, which is provided by thelength, circular folds, villi and microvilli

Figure 25.25

Figure 25.26

The small intestine motility

  • Motility of the small intestine performs:
    • Mixing ofchymewith intestinal juice, bile, pancreaticjuice
    • To bring chime in contact with the mucosa fordigestion and absorption
    • Move reside towards the large intestine
  • Motility patterns include:
    • Segmentation
      • Stationary contractions, short/long orally/anallypropagating contractions
    • Peristalsis
      • Short/long anally propagating contractions
    • Migrating motorcomplex
      • Slow anally propagating contractions thatextend most of the length of intestine

Furness & Costa, 1980

The enteric nervous system

The enteric nervoussystem is containedentirely within the walls ofthe intestine. It can controlall the motor patterns andsecretions, although undernormal conditions receivesmodulation from the CNS.It is able to do this becauseit complete completeneural circuits.

Chemical digestion: Enzymes

Video: Enzyme Action andthe Hydrolysis of Sucrose

Chemical digestion and absorption

  • Carbohydrates
    • Mostly starch, cellulose is ingestible, tiny amountof glycogen
    • Starch is digested into oligosaccharides, thendisaccharide maltose, then glucose, which isabsorbed by the small intestine
    • Digestion starts with amylase in the saliva andpancreatic juice, also stomach acid
    • Dextrinaseandglucoamylasehydrolyseoligosaccharides
    • Maltase hydrolyses maltose
    • Transport proteins quickly absorb themonosaccharides

Figure23.29

Chemical digestion and absorption

  • Proteins
    • Absorbed proteins come not only from dietary proteins, but also self-digested enzymes and epithelialcells
    • First hydrolysed by pepsin (in the stomach only) to make shorter polypeptides
    • In small intestine, pancreatic enzymestrysinand chymotrypsin hydrolyse polypeptides intooligopeptides
    • Finally, carboxypeptidase (-COOH), aminopeptidase (-NH2) anddipeptidasecreate free amino acids
    • Enterocytes have several sodium-dependent amino acid cotransporters for absorption
    • In infants, intact proteins can be absorbed by pinocytosis, which allows IgA from breast milk to enterthe blood stream

Chemical digestion and absorption

  • Lipids
    • In the mouth, lingual lipase starts the digestion of fat, but becomes more active with the acidic pH ofthe stomach
    • In the stomach, gastric lipase also digests fats
    • Antral pumping breaks large globules of fat into emulsified droplets, which is broken up further in thesmall intestine by segmentation
    • In the small intestine, pancreatic lipase acts on triglyceride to produce two free fatty acids and amonoglyceride
    • About 50% of dietary fat can diffuse across through the plasma membrane into enterocytes
    • Micelles, made in the liver enter the duodenum via the bile duct, where they absorb fat solublevitamins, cholesterol, free fatty acids and monoglycerides
      • Micelles release contents into enterocytes
    • In the enterocytes, fats are resynthesized into triglycerides and coated with phospholipids andproteins to chylomicrons, which are secreted from the enterocytes and taken up by the lacteals

Chemical digestion andabsorption

Figure23.32

Chemical digestion and absorption

  • Nucleic acids
    • DNA and RNA are hydrolysed into nucleotides by nucleases in pancreatic juices
    • Enzymes on the brush border decompose them into phosphate ions, nitrogen bases and simplesugars, which are transported across the epithelium
  • Vitamins
    • Are not digested, but absorbed unchanged
    • Fat-soluble vitamins are absorbed with other lipids
    • Water-soluble vitamins are absorbed by simple diffusion
    • Except vitamin B12, which bind to intrinsic factor (released by parietal cells) and absorbed in theileum via endocytosis
  • Minerals
    • Most minerals are absorbed by transporters through the intestine without regulation
    • Iron binds to enterocytes and requires active transport, which is under hormonal regulation
    • Calcium is absorbed by a transcellular route in the duodenum (under hormonal control) and by aparacellular route in the jejunum and ileum (independent of hormones)
  • Water is absorbed by osmosis

Large intestine

Figure23.33

Large intestine

  • Intestinal microbes
    • The gut microbiome forms a mutually beneficial relationship by providing us with nutrients we can’tdigest by ourselves (e.g. cellulose and Vitamin K)
  • Absorption
    • No chemical change to the residue (except from microbes), but reabsorbs water and electrolytes
  • Motility
    • Haustralcontractions occur in response to distention, they churn and mix the residue to promoteabsorption
    • Mass movements are strong contractions that move residue several centimetres at time
      • Often triggered by reflexes initiated by filling of the stomach and/or duodenum

Large intestine

  • Defecation
    • Intrinsic defecation reflex is mediated entirely by the myenteric plexus,which initiates peristaltic waves and sphincter relaxation
    • Parasympathetic defecation reflex is a spinal reflex that initiatesperistaltic waves and sphincter relaxation
